<subSubSection pageId="189" pageNumber="792" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="189.[2049,2642,2785,3204]" lastBlockId="189.[1436,2641,3211,3479]" pageId="189" pageNumber="792">
Based on cytochrome-b sequences and morphology (e.g. proodont incisors), con- sidered by J. Bryja and colleagues in 2014 to be part of the 
<taxonomicName box="[2295,2373,3052,3086]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="189" pageNumber="792" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sorella">sorella</taxonomicName>
species group; dis- tinguishable from 
<taxonomicName box="[2316,2443,3091,3125]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="189" pageNumber="792" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sorella">M. sorella</taxonomicName>
by its smaller size, smaller maxillary toothrow, and rich- er “bright tawny” coloration, as compared to dark gray. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="189" pageNumber="792" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6888076" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6888076" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6888076/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="189" pageNumber="792" startId="189.[1436,1608,3257,3282]" targetBox="[1435,2027,2787,3203]" targetPageId="189">
<paragraph blockId="189.[1436,2641,3211,3479]" pageId="189" pageNumber="792">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1436,1612,3257,3282]" pageId="189" pageNumber="792">Distribution.</emphasis>
Based on molecular vouchers it occurs in E Zambia, Malawi, and Tanzania; records from N Mozambique, Zimbabwe, and N South Africa lack genetic verification, but are included here.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="190" lastPageNumber="793" pageId="189" pageNumber="792" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="189.[1436,2641,3211,3479]" lastBlockId="190.[91,1297,294,642]" lastPageId="190" lastPageNumber="793" pageId="189" pageNumber="792">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1436,1687,3375,3400]" pageId="189" pageNumber="792">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 58-106 mm, tail 33-48 mm, ear 10-12 mm, hindfoot 12-14 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Neave’s Mouse is a small to medium-sized rodent with short tail. Fur is ocherous-brown to rich tawny-brown above and pure white below. Tail is short (c.43% of head-body length). Ears are large and pale gray. Feet are white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
